(b) Ionic Radius

The removal of an electron from an atom results in the formation of a cation, whereas gain of an electron leads to an anion.", "fibs": ["b"]}
{"text": "In general, the ionic radii of elements exhibit the same trend as the atomic radii.", "fibs": ["exhibit"]}
{"text": "A cation is smaller than its parent atom because it has fewer electrons while its nuclear charge remains the same.", "fibs": ["cation"]}
{"text": "The size of an anion will be larger than that of the parent atom because the addition of one or more electrons would result in increased repulsion among the electrons and a decrease in effective nuclear charge.", "fibs": ["size"]}
{"text": "For example, the ionic radius of fluoride ion (F– ) is 136 pm whereas the atomic radius of fluorine is only 64 pm.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "On the other hand, the atomic radius of sodium is 186 pm compared to the ionic radius of 95 pm for Na+.", "fibs": ["hand"]}
{"text": "When we find some atoms and ions which contain the same number of electrons, we call them isoelectronic species*.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "For example, O2–, F–, Na+ and Mg2+ have the same number of electrons (10).", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "The cation with the greater positive charge will have a smaller radius because of the greater attraction of the electrons to the nucleus.", "fibs": ["cation"]}
{"text": "Anion with the greater negative charge will have the larger radius.", "fibs": ["Anion"]}
{"text": "In this case, the net repulsion of the electrons will outweigh the nuclear charge and the ion will expand in size.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "Problem 3.5
Which of the following species will have the largest and the smallest size?", "fibs": ["species"]}
{"text": "Mg, Mg2+, Al, Al3+.", "fibs": ["Mg"]}
{"text": "Solution
Atomic radii decrease across a period.", "fibs": ["decrease"]}
{"text": "Cations are smaller than their parent atoms.", "fibs": ["parent"]}
{"text": "Among isoelectronic species, the one with the larger positive nuclear charge will have a smaller radius.", "fibs": ["isoelectronic"]}
{"text": "Hence the largest species is Mg; the smallest one is Al3+.", "fibs": ["species"]}
{"text": "(c)	Ionization Enthalpy
A quantitative measure of the tendency of an element to lose electron is given by its Ionization Enthalpy.", "fibs": ["measure"]}
{"text": "It represents the energy required to remove an electron from an isolated gaseous atom (X) in its ground state.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "In other words, the first ionization enthalpy for an element X is the enthalpy change (∆i H) for the reaction depicted in equation 3.1.", "fibs": ["ionization"]}
{"text": "X(g) → X+(g) + e–  (3.1)
The ionization enthalpy is expressed in units of kJ mol–1.", "fibs": ["X(g"]}
{"text": "We can define the second ionization enthalpy as the energy required to remove the second most loosely bound electron; it is the energy required to carry out the reaction shown in equation 3.2.", "fibs": ["ionization"]}
{"text": "X+(g) → X2+(g) + e–	(3.2)
Energy is always required to remove electrons from an atom and hence ionization enthalpies are always positive.", "fibs": ["X+(g"]}
{"text": "The second ionization enthalpy will be higher than the first ionization enthalpy because it is more difficult to remove an electron from a positively charged ion than from a neutral atom.", "fibs": ["ionization"]}
{"text": "In the same way the third ionization enthalpy will be higher than the second and so on.", "fibs": ["way"]}
{"text": "The term “ionization enthalpy”, if not qualified, is taken as the first ionization enthalpy.", "fibs": ["term"]}
{"text": "* Two or more species with same number of atoms, same number of valence electrons and same structure, regardless of the nature of elements involved.", "fibs": ["species"]}
{"text": "The first ionization enthalpies of elements having atomic numbers up to 60 are plotted in Fig.", "fibs": ["ionization"]}
{"text": "The periodicity of the graph is quite striking.", "fibs": ["periodicity"]}
{"text": "You will find maxima at the noble gases which have closed electron shells and very stable electron configurations.", "fibs": ["maxima"]}
{"text": "On the other hand, minima occur at the alkali metals and their low ionization enthalpies can be correlated with their high reactivity.", "fibs": ["hand"]}
{"text": "In addition, you will notice two trends  the first ionization enthalpy generally increases as we go across a period and decreases as we descend in a group.", "fibs": ["addition"]}
{"text": "3.6(a) and 3.6(b) respectively for the elements of the second period and the first group of the periodic table.", "fibs": ["3.6(a"]}
{"text": "You will appreciate that the ionization enthalpy and atomic radius are closely related properties.", "fibs": ["ionization"]}
{"text": "To understand these trends, we have to consider two factors : (i) the attraction of electrons towards the nucleus, and (ii) the repulsion of electrons from each other.", "fibs": ["attraction"]}
{"text": "The effective nuclear charge experienced by a valence electron in an atom will be less than the actual charge on the nucleus because of “shielding” or “screening” of the valence electron from the nucleus by the intervening core electrons.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "For example, the 2s electron in lithium is shielded from the nucleus by the inner core of 1s electrons.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "As a result, the valence electron experiences a net positive charge which is  less than the actual charge of +3.", "fibs": ["result"]}
{"text": "In general, shielding is effective when the orbitals in the inner shells are completely filled.", "fibs": ["shielding"]}
{"text": "This situation occurs in the case of alkali metals which have single outermost ns-electron preceded by a noble gas electronic configuration.", "fibs": ["situation"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "3.5 Variation of first ionization enthalpies (∆iH) with atomic number for elements with Z = 1 to 60





