Fig.", "fibs": ["ionization"]}
{"text": "3.6(a) First ionization enthalpies (∆iH) of elements of the second period as a function of atomic number (Z) and Fig.", "fibs": ["3.6(a"]}
{"text": "3.6(b) ∆iH of alkali metals as a function of Z.", "fibs": ["3.6(b"]}
{"text": "When we move from lithium to fluorine across the second period, successive electrons are added to orbitals in the same principal quantum level and the shielding of the nuclear charge by the inner core of electrons does not increase very much to compensate for the increased attraction of the electron to the nucleus.", "fibs": ["move"]}
{"text": "Thus, across a period, increasing nuclear charge outweighs the shielding.", "fibs": ["period"]}
{"text": "Consequently, the outermost electrons are held more and more tightly and the ionization enthalpy increases across a period.", "fibs": ["outermost"]}
{"text": "As we go down a group, the outermost electron being increasingly farther from the nucleus, there is an increased shielding of the nuclear charge by the electrons in the inner levels.", "fibs": ["group"]}
{"text": "In this case, increase in shielding outweighs the increasing nuclear charge and the removal of the outermost electron requires less energy down a group.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "From Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "3.6(a), you will also notice that the first ionization enthalpy of boron (Z = 5) is slightly less than that of beryllium (Z = 4) even though the former has a greater nuclear charge.", "fibs": ["3.6(a"]}
{"text": "When we consider the same principal quantum level, an s-electron is attracted to the nucleus more than a p-electron.", "fibs": ["quantum"]}
{"text": "In beryllium, the electron removed during the ionization is an s-electron whereas the electron removed during ionization of boron is a p-electron.", "fibs": ["beryllium"]}
{"text": "The penetration of a 2s-electron to the nucleus is more than that of a 2p-electron; hence the 2p electron of boron is more shielded from the nucleus by the inner core of electrons than the 2s electrons of beryllium.", "fibs": ["penetration"]}
{"text": "Therefore, it is easier to remove the 2p-electron from boron compared to the removal of a 2s- electron from beryllium.", "fibs": ["boron"]}
{"text": "Thus, boron has a smaller first ionization enthalpy than beryllium.", "fibs": ["boron"]}
{"text": "Another “anomaly” is the smaller first ionization enthalpy of oxygen compared to nitrogen.", "fibs": ["anomaly"]}
{"text": "This arises because in the nitrogen atom, three 2p-electrons reside in different atomic orbitals (Hund’s rule) whereas in the oxygen atom, two of the four 2p-electrons must occupy the same 2p-orbital resulting in an increased electron-electron repulsion.", "fibs": ["nitrogen"]}
{"text": "Consequently, it is easier to remove the fourth 2p-electron from oxygen than it is, to remove one of the three 2p-electrons from nitrogen.", "fibs": ["oxygen"]}
{"text": "Problem 3.6	
The first ionization enthalpy (∆i H ) values of the third period elements, Na, Mg and Si are respectively 496, 737 and 786 kJ mol–1.", "fibs": ["ionization"]}
{"text": "Predict whether the first ∆i H value for Al will be more close to 575 or 760 kJ mol–1 ?", "fibs": ["∆i"]}
{"text": "Justify your answer.", "fibs": ["answer"]}
{"text": "Solution 
It will be more close to 575 kJ mol–1.", "fibs": ["kJ"]}
{"text": "The value for Al should be lower than that of Mg because of effective shielding of 3p electrons from the nucleus by 3s-electrons.", "fibs": ["value"]}
{"text": "(d) Electron Gain Enthalpy
When an electron is added to a neutral gaseous atom (X) to convert it into a negative ion, the enthalpy change accompanying the process is defined as the Electron Gain Enthalpy (∆egH).", "fibs": ["Gain"]}
{"text": "Electron gain enthalpy provides a measure of the ease with which an atom adds an electron to form anion as represented by equation 3.3.", "fibs": ["gain"]}
{"text": "X(g) + e–  → X–(g)	 (3.3)
Depending on the element, the process of adding an electron to the atom can be either endothermic or exothermic.", "fibs": ["X(g"]}
{"text": "For many elements energy is released when an electron is added to the atom and the electron gain enthalpy is negative.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "For example, group 17 elements (the halogens) have very high negative electron gain enthalpies because they can attain stable noble gas electronic configurations by picking up an electron.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "On the other hand, noble gases have large positive electron gain enthalpies because the electron has to enter the next higher principal quantum level leading to a very unstable electronic configuration.", "fibs": ["hand"]}
{"text": "It may be noted that electron gain enthalpies have large negative values toward the upper right of the periodic table preceding the noble gases.", "fibs": ["electron"]}
{"text": "Table 3.7  Electron Gain Enthalpies* / (kJ mol–1) of Some Main Group Elements




The variation in electron gain enthalpies of elements is less systematic than for ionization enthalpies.", "fibs": ["Table"]}
{"text": "As a general rule, electron gain enthalpy becomes more negative with increase in the atomic number across a period.", "fibs": ["rule"]}
{"text": "The effective nuclear charge increases from left to right across a period and consequently it will be easier to add an electron to a smaller atom since the added electron on an average would be closer to the positively charged nucleus.", "fibs": ["charge"]}
{"text": "We should also expect electron gain enthalpy to become less negative as we go down a group because the size of the atom increases and the added electron would be farther from the nucleus.", "fibs": ["electron"]}
{"text": "This is generally the case (Table 3.7).", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "However, electron gain enthalpy of O or F is less negative than that of the succeeding element.", "fibs": ["electron"]}
{"text": "This is because when an electron is added to O or F, the added electron goes to the smaller n = 2 quantum level and suffers significant repulsion from the other electrons present in this level.", "fibs": ["electron"]}
{"text": "For the n = 3 quantum level (S or Cl), the added electron occupies a larger region of space and the electron-electron repulsion is much less.", "fibs": ["quantum"]}
{"text": "Problem 3.7
Which of the following will have the most negative electron gain enthalpy and which the least negative?", "fibs": ["electron"]}
{"text": "P, S, Cl, F.
Explain your answer.", "fibs": ["P"]}
{"text": "Solution
Electron gain enthalpy generally becomes more negative across a period as we move from left to right.", "fibs": ["gain"]}
{"text": "Within a group, electron gain enthalpy becomes less negative down a group.", "fibs": ["group"]}
{"text": "However, adding an electron to the 2p-orbital leads to greater repulsion than adding an electron to the larger 3p-orbital.", "fibs": ["electron"]}
{"text": "Hence the element with most negative electron gain enthalpy is chlorine; the one with the least negative electron gain enthalpy is phosphorus.", "fibs": ["element"]}
{"text": "(e) Electronegativity
A qualitative measure of the ability of an atom in a chemical compound to attract shared electrons to itself is called electronegativity.", "fibs": ["measure"]}
{"text": "Unlike ionization enthalpy and electron gain enthalpy, it is not a measureable quantity.", "fibs": ["ionization"]}
{"text": "However, a number of numerical scales of electronegativity of elements viz., Pauling scale, Mulliken-Jaffe scale, Allred-Rochow scale have been developed.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "The one which is the most widely used is the Pauling scale.", "fibs": ["scale"]}
{"text": "Linus Pauling, an American scientist, in 1922 assigned arbitrarily a value of 4.0 to fluorine, the element considered to have the greatest ability to attract electrons.", "fibs": ["scientist"]}
{"text": "Approximate values for the electronegativity of a few elements are given in Table 3.8(a)


* In many books, the negative of the enthalpy change for the process depicted in equation 3.3 is defined as the ELECTRON AFFINITY (Ae ) of the atom under consideration.", "fibs": ["electronegativity"]}
{"text": "If energy is released when an electron is added to an atom, the electron affinity is taken as positive, contrary to thermodynamic convention.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "If energy has to be supplied to add an electron to an atom, then the electron affinity of the atom is assigned a negative sign.", "fibs": ["energy"]}
{"text": "However, electron affinity is defined as absolute zero and, therefore at any other temperature (T) heat capacities of the reactants and the products have to be taken into account in ∆egH = –Ae – 5/2 RT.", "fibs": ["electron"]}
{"text": "The electronegativity of any given element is not constant; it varies depending on the element to which it is bound.", "fibs": ["electronegativity"]}
{"text": "Though it is not a measurable quantity, it does provide a means of predicting the nature of force that holds a pair of atoms together – a relationship that you will explore later.", "fibs": ["quantity"]}
{"text": "Electronegativity generally increases across a period from left to right (say from lithium to fluorine) and decrease down a group (say from fluorine to astatine) in the periodic table.", "fibs": ["period"]}
{"text": "Can the electronegativity be related to atomic radii, which tend to decrease across each period from left to right, but increase down each group ?", "fibs": ["electronegativity"]}
{"text": "The attraction between the outer (or valence) electrons and the nucleus increases as the atomic radius decreases in a period.", "fibs": ["attraction"]}
{"text": "The electronegativity also increases.", "fibs": ["electronegativity"]}
{"text": "On the same account electronegativity values decrease with the increase in atomic radii down a group.", "fibs": ["account"]}
{"text": "The trend is similar to that of ionization enthalpy.", "fibs": ["trend"]}
{"text": "Fig.", "fibs": ["Fig"]}
{"text": "3.7  The periodic trends of elements in the periodic table



Knowing the relationship between electronegativity and atomic radius, can you now visualise the relationship between electronegativity and non-metallic properties?", "fibs": ["table"]}
{"text": "Non-metallic  elements have strong tendency to gain electrons.", "fibs": ["tendency"]}
{"text": "Therefore, electronegativity is directly related to that non-metallic properties of elements.", "fibs": ["electronegativity"]}
{"text": "It can be further extended to say that the electronegativity is inversely related to the metallic properties of elements.", "fibs": ["electronegativity"]}
{"text": "Thus, the increase in electronegativities across a period is accompanied by an increase in non-metallic properties (or decrease in metallic properties) of elements.", "fibs": ["increase"]}
{"text": "Similarly, the decrease in electronegativity down a group is accompanied by a decrease in non-metallic properties (or increase in metallic properties) of elements.", "fibs": ["decrease"]}
{"text": "All these periodic trends are summarised in figure 3.7.", "fibs": ["figure"]}
